        How to Prepare for Your First Meeting with a Real Estate Agent in Brisbane
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Your first meeting with an agent is more valuable if you arrive prepared. Here is what to bring, what to ask, and how to compare multiple appraisals fairly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane homeowners call an agent when they are ready to sell, but the more useful time to have that first conversation is three to six months earlier. An initial appraisal meeting is not a commitment to sell or to use that particular agent. It is an information-gathering exercise, and the more prepared you are walking in, the more you will get out of it. Agents who know you have done your homework tend to give sharper, more honest assessments rather than a broad range designed to manage expectations either way.</p>

      <p>Before any meeting, spend an hour reviewing recent sales in your street and immediate surrounds. CoreLogic, Domain, and the relevant council property data all have recent sales history. You do not need to become an expert, but having a sense of what similar properties achieved in the past twelve months gives you a baseline. When an agent quotes you a price range, you will be able to assess whether it reflects actual recent evidence or wishful thinking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to bring to the meeting</h2>
      <p>The most useful documents to have on hand are your title documents, your most recent council rates notice, and your water rates notice. The title documents confirm boundaries, any easements on the property, and existing caveats or encumbrances that a buyer will eventually uncover. Agents use the council and water rates for comparison because some buyers factor holding costs into their offers. If you have a body corporate (unit or townhouse), bring the most recent levy notice and sinking fund balance if you have it.</p>

      <p>If you have an existing mortgage, you do not need to share the balance, but knowing roughly what you owe relative to your expected sale price will help you assess the financial case for selling now versus later. You should also have a general sense of any capital improvements you have made since purchase: a new kitchen, bathroom renovation, new roof, or deck addition all affect the agent's estimate and your conversations about comparable sales. Bring receipts or at least rough figures if you have them.</p>

      <p>Any council notices about unapproved structures, pending approvals, or notices of intention are worth disclosing to the agent at this stage. Queensland's property disclosure obligations mean buyers will find out, and agents who know about these issues early can advise you on how to address them before listing rather than managing them mid-campaign when they tend to cause more damage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions worth asking every agent</h2>
      <p>A first meeting is as much an interview of the agent as it is an appraisal of your property. The questions that reveal the most about how an agent operates are the ones about process and evidence, not personality or enthusiasm. Ask them to show you three comparable sales they have achieved in the past six months in your suburb or adjoining suburbs, and ask them to walk you through the differences between each of those properties and yours. The quality of that answer tells you whether their price estimate is grounded in real data or in what they think you want to hear.</p>

      <p>Ask whether they recommend auction or private treaty for your property, and why. In Brisbane's inner east, auction is often the right choice for well-presented homes in active price brackets, but not universally. A good agent should be able to explain the trade-offs clearly: auction creates urgency and competition but requires unconditional offers on the day; private treaty suits buyers who need finance approval and can attract serious offers from buyers who resist auction conditions. If an agent pushes a method without being able to articulate the reasoning for your specific property, that is a signal.</p>

      <p>Ask about their marketing plan in concrete terms: which platforms, what photography and video, whether they use floor plans and property styling referrals, and what the out-of-pocket marketing costs will be. Ask how many active buyers they are currently working with who fit your property's profile. You should also ask directly about their commission structure and whether it is negotiable. A confident agent will answer plainly; an evasive answer here is worth noting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the agent is assessing during the walkthrough</h2>
      <p>While you are showing them the property, a good agent is mentally categorising what will help and what will hurt the campaign. They are looking at the kitchen and main bathroom first, because these are the rooms that most consistently drive buyer decisions in Brisbane's inner-east market. They are assessing the condition of the external paintwork, the state of the garden and fencing, and any deferred maintenance items that buyers will use to justify lower offers or additional conditions.</p>

      <p>They are also assessing the home's functional layout relative to what the current buyer pool is looking for. A well-maintained but functionally dated property may need different preparation advice than a recently renovated home that simply needs styling and cleaning. The most useful feedback an agent can give at this stage is a frank prioritised list: what to spend money on before listing, what to leave alone, and what buyers will simply accept as is. If they are vague on this, push them for specifics.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to compare multiple appraisals fairly</h2>
      <p>If you are meeting with two or three agents, the instinct is to compare them on their price estimates. That is understandable, but price estimates vary for reasons that have nothing to do with expertise. Some agents quote high to win the listing and then manage your expectations down once you are signed. Others are conservative because they are cautious about the current market. The number itself tells you less than how it was reached.</p>

      <p>Compare agents on the quality of their comparable evidence, the clarity of their marketing plan, the concreteness of their preparation advice, and how directly they answered your questions. An agent who quotes $100,000 higher but cannot back it up with comparable sales evidence is a risk to your campaign; an agent who quotes slightly lower but can explain precisely why, and what you can do to push it higher, is a more credible choice. Also compare their availability: ask who specifically handles your campaign day to day, and whether you will have direct access to them or be handed to a junior team member after sign-up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Red flags to watch for</h2>
      <p>The most common warning signs in an agent pitch are easy to miss in the moment. An agent who avoids giving you a specific price range or qualifying conditions, preferring to "see how the market responds," may lack the conviction to negotiate hard on your behalf when offers come in. An agent who focuses heavily on their office's overall market share rather than on their own personal results for comparable properties is worth questioning further.</p>

      <p>Any suggestion to list at a price significantly above recent comparable sales "to test the market" is generally a mistake. Overpriced listings in Brisbane's inner east lose momentum quickly, and a property that sits on the market for six weeks will attract a different quality of buyer than one that generates competitive interest in the first two. The best outcomes almost always come from accurate pricing from day one combined with strong presentation and active follow-through from the agent.</p>

